What if your budget phone could run tasks on your flagship's hardware — over your home Wi-Fi?

That's the idea behind my latest C++ prototype: Distributed Personal Resource Virtualization (DPRV).

The concept is simple:
→ Low-end devices (phones, tablets) send an Assign packet to a controller (flagship device at your home)
→ The controller picks a free high-end worker using round-robin + fallback
→ Both devices get a Connect packet — they now know each other
→ The client sends a Data packet directly to the worker(high-end device), bypasses the controller
→ Result comes back. Job done.

No cloud. No subscription. Just your own devices sharing power with each other.

Under the hood I applied 4 design patterns:
• Template Method — to define the task flow skeleton
• Strategy — for packet creation steps
• Command + Bridge — in the controller's receiver logic
• Round Robin with fallback — for core assignment

Still a prototype, but the architecture holds up. Would love to build this into something real someday.
